of individuals and groups. A practical exercise in Canadian contextual theology, Rage and Resistance analyzes responses to a tragic historical event by engaging with the work of theologian Gregory Baum and sociologist Dorothy Smith. Baum articulates the theological imperative to address the context in which our lives are embedded, calling for critical social analysis in order to understand, and possibly convert, social evil; Smith takes the standpoint of women as a determinate position from which society may be known. If one of the tasks of theology is to articulate and clarify the struggles in which we are engaged—to name our reality, both the forces that oppress and the possibilities for resistance and healing—this book takes on that task by focusing on an event indelibly etched into the minds of many Canadians. It analyzes some of the artistic, memorializing, and activist responses as manifestations of a spirituality of resistance and urges ever greater resistance to violence against women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianisme et civilisationxCanadaxCanada. 0aChristianity and culturexCanada. 0aChristianity and culturezCanada. 0aChurch and social problems. 0aFemmes, Crimes contre lesxAspect religieuxxChristianisme. 0aMontréal École Polytechnique Women Students Massacre, Montréal, Québec, 1989. 0aPassive resistance. 0aRésistance passive. 0aViolence envers les femmes. 0aWomenxCrimes againstxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aWomenxViolence against. 0aÉglise et problèmes sociaux. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package p